  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 4.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "I knew that thou art obstinate;",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " literally, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "hard",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "stiff - the",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " adjective used in the phrase translated in our version \"stiff-necked.\" The idea is still more forcibly expressed in the following clause ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "- thy neck is an iron sinew;",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " or rather, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "a band of iron",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "as",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " stiff as if it were made-of the hardest metal. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And thy brow brass",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The exact simile here used does not occur elsewhere in Scripture. It seems to be the origin of our expressions, \"brazen,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "...",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " brazen-faced,\" \"to brazen a thing out.\" The forehead may be hardened for a good or for a bad purpose; in obstinacy or in a determination to resist evil (comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 1:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 3:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 5:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 3:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Zechariah 7:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Here the hardening is evil, marking defiance and self-will. Isaiah 48:4",
